1. Install Grafana Loki: First, you need to have Grafana Loki installed and running. Grafana Loki is a high-performance, open-source, and easy-to-use log management system. You can find the installation instructions in the Grafana Loki documentation: https://grafana.com/docs/loki/installation/

2. Configure your Yii2 application to use a logging library that supports sending logs to an HTTP endpoint. One popular choice is Monolog, which is a PHP logging library that can be easily integrated with Yii2. You can install Monolog using Composer: https://packagist.org/packages/monolog/monolog

3. Create a custom Monolog handler that sends logs to Grafana Loki. You can create a new PHP class that extends the `Monolog\Handler\StreamHandler` class and implements the `Monolog\Handler\HandlerInterface` interface. In this handler, you'll need to make HTTP requests to Grafana Loki using a library like Guzzle or curl.

Here's an example of how you can create a custom Monolog handler:

```php
use Monolog\Handler\StreamHandler;
use Monolog\Handler\HandlerInterface;
use GuzzleHttp\Client;

class GrafanaLokiHandler implements HandlerInterface
{
    private $client;
    private $url;
    private $token;

    public function __construct(string $url, string $token)
    {
        $this->client = new Client();
        $this->url = $url;
        $this->token = $token;
    }

    public function handle(array $record): void
    {
        $json = json_encode(['level' => $record['level'], 'message' => $record['message']]);
        $this->client->post($this->url, ['json' => $json, 'headers' => ['Authorization' => 'Bearer ' . $this->token]]);
    }
}
```

4. Configure your Yii2 application to use the custom Monolog handler. You can do this by adding the handler to the ` Yii2` application's `log` component in the ` Yii2` application configuration file (`config/web.php`):

```php
'components' => [
    'log' => [
        'class' => 'Monolog\Handler\StreamHandler',
        'level' => 'info',
        'handler' => [
            'class' => 'YourNamespace\GrafanaLokiHandler',
            'url' => 'https://your-loki-instance/api',
            'token' => 'your-loki-token',
        ],
    ],
],
```

5. Finally, make sure to replace the placeholders in the code with your actual Grafana Loki URL, token, and any other necessary configuration.

